\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5251090 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4152482\charrsid3281826 m. In your district of London who were considered the most important peo
ple? Did you come into contact with them? Why were they considered important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5251090 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4152482\charrsid3281826 
Here again, important people rarely cut across their life. Doctors had to be paid and so most people 'doctored themselves'. Although the church was more important then, he n
ever came into contact with clegymen. Therefore the idea of 'important people' never seems to have concerned them. Mr. Mennie added that their main concern was earning their bread.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5251090 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4152482\charrsid3281826 Where you lived, did all the people in the working class have the same standard of living, or would you say there were different groups?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5251090 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4152482\charrsid3281826 
No real distinction at all. One single community with no rigid barriers. The shopkeepers were slightly better off, but they were not apart as a distinct group. No one was really out to better himself.
